AB  - The process of swing amplification is discussed as a possible mechanism to account for the spiral structure of galaxies. The mechanism is proposed to occur in a thin infinite disk of stars with a Gaussian spread of radial velocities orbiting in a force field corresponding to the flattest imaginable law of circular motion, with half of the central force field coming from a rigid and fixed spheroidal halo, which is subject to disturbances resulting from weak, transient external quadrupole forces revolving counterclockwise with the same angular speed as the test particles in the outermost circles. The amplification is shown to result from a combination of galactic shear flow, epicyclic shaking and self-gravity, and to be characterized by oscillations with amplitudes about four times larger than kinematic and arms wound more tightly and of greater density than kinematic features. The unstable spiral modes of a Gaussian disk are then examined, and implications of the swing amplification theory for the prevention of violent bar-making instabilities of disks and the lifetimes of the spiral patterns in normal spirals such as M51 and M81 are noted.
